WEBVTT

1
00:00:06.631 --> 00:00:08.967
[birds chirping]

2
00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:16.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

3
00:00:17.642 --> 00:00:19.477
[insects buzzing]

4
00:00:28.236 --> 00:00:30.238
[distant whistling]

5
00:00:41.207 --> 00:00:43.209
[whistling continues]

6
00:00:56.848 --> 00:00:58.850
[poignant music playing]

7
00:01:10.111 --> 00:01:12.238
[poignant music playing]

8
00:01:15.408 --> 00:01:17.327
[Charles laughs]

9
00:01:19.913 --> 00:01:21.581
[exclaims]

10
00:01:21.664 --> 00:01:24.000
Oh. George. what are you doing here?

11
00:01:24.501 --> 00:01:28.171
- How are you? How did you find us?
- You gave up on me. Charlie.

12
00:01:32.634 --> 00:01:33.510
I didn't.

13
00:01:37.889 --> 00:01:38.723
[Laura] Pa?

14
00:01:39.432 --> 00:01:40.558
Pa.

15
00:01:41.768 --> 00:01:43.478
Who were you talking to?

16
00:01:48.691 --> 00:01:49.526
No one.

17
00:01:50.819 --> 00:01:51.903
[Charles scoffs]

18
00:01:53.571 --> 00:01:55.698
Come on. Let's go.

19
00:02:08.002 --> 00:02:09.295
[music fades]

20
00:02:09.379 --> 00:02:11.339
[birds chirping]

21
00:02:11.422 --> 00:02:13.091
Your mother said
as soon as you could walk.

22
00:02:13.174 --> 00:02:16.177
she'd find you half a mile
down the road in the middle of the night.

23
00:02:16.886 --> 00:02:18.805
Restless legs. she said.

24
00:02:20.223 --> 00:02:23.643
Well. hopefully. our son
will take after you and not after me.

25
00:02:26.563 --> 00:02:30.108
I was thinking George for a name.

26
00:02:30.608 --> 00:02:31.943
[tender music playing]

27
00:02:32.026 --> 00:02:32.902
I like it.

28
00:02:35.655 --> 00:02:36.948
[Jack barking]

29
00:02:37.031 --> 00:02:39.868
[Mary and Laura laughing]

30
00:02:39.951 --> 00:02:41.327
This won't keep.

31
00:02:51.838 --> 00:02:52.881
It's good news.

32
00:02:53.381 --> 00:02:54.799
What are we waiting for?

33
00:02:55.466 --> 00:02:56.342
[Caroline laughs]

34
00:02:56.426 --> 00:03:00.638
Ah! It's a girl! I know it's a girl.
It has to be a girl.

35
00:03:00.722 --> 00:03:03.433
- You don't think we're overdue for a boy?
- No.

36
00:03:03.516 --> 00:03:04.684
Can I name her?

37
00:03:04.767 --> 00:03:08.354
Please. Do you think I could get
some muslin and make a bonnet for her?

38
00:03:08.438 --> 00:03:10.899
- Let's not put the cart before the horse.
- Ma!

39
00:03:10.982 --> 00:03:13.610
What do you think. Half Pint? Any bets?

40
00:03:15.570 --> 00:03:16.446
No.

41
00:03:19.240 --> 00:03:22.327
Either way.
it'll be lucky to have a sister like you.

42
00:03:26.831 --> 00:03:28.708
- [Mary laughs excitedly]
- [Caroline chuckles]

43
00:03:38.593 --> 00:03:39.886
[music fades]

44
00:03:39.969 --> 00:03:42.889
["Weevily Wheat" playing on the harmonica]

45
00:03:49.312 --> 00:03:52.690
- My uncle George used to sing that.
- I come bearing gifts.

46
00:03:53.191 --> 00:03:56.027
Coffee. candy. and coneflowers.

47
00:03:57.028 --> 00:03:58.196
Here you go.

48
00:03:59.322 --> 00:04:00.573
[Laura] Peppermint sticks!

49
00:04:01.241 --> 00:04:02.575
[Mr. Edwards] And these

50
00:04:03.076 --> 00:04:04.118
are for your ma.

51
00:04:04.619 --> 00:04:05.787
Thank you.

52
00:04:07.538 --> 00:04:09.415
We did say first thing in the morning.
didn't we?

53
00:04:10.667 --> 00:04:11.542
We did.

54
00:04:12.210 --> 00:04:13.044
Yeah.

55
00:04:16.547 --> 00:04:17.465
[Laura chuckles]

56
00:04:24.222 --> 00:04:25.265
I'm saving mine.

57
00:04:25.348 --> 00:04:26.641
Go ahead.

58
00:04:27.267 --> 00:04:29.352
It'll just get all sticky in your pocket.

59
00:04:31.271 --> 00:04:32.897
[sawing]

60
00:04:36.150 --> 00:04:38.152
[Charles] You're a better carpenter
than I am.

61
00:04:38.236 --> 00:04:40.363
Could have easily gotten
a house built by now.

62
00:04:40.446 --> 00:04:43.366
Ah. like I said.
wasn't sure if I was stayin'. Ready?

63
00:04:43.449 --> 00:04:44.367
[grunts]

64
00:04:45.451 --> 00:04:47.787
- But I'll take the compliment.
- [Charles grunts]

65
00:04:49.747 --> 00:04:51.124
[Mr. Edwards sniffs]

66
00:04:51.207 --> 00:04:55.545
I can't help thinking about what you said.
This land isn't open for settlement.

67
00:04:56.045 --> 00:04:57.171
Did I say that?

68
00:04:57.839 --> 00:04:59.424
No. I didn't say that.

69
00:05:00.633 --> 00:05:04.304
You said it belonged to the Osage.
You said they'd be back.

70
00:05:04.887 --> 00:05:07.849
- Well. if it does. then they will.
- [Charles grunts]

71
00:05:09.600 --> 00:05:11.269
Take a look around. Ingalls.

72
00:05:12.186 --> 00:05:16.274
These settlers are like a prairie fire.
Prairie fire can't be stopped.

73
00:05:16.357 --> 00:05:18.192
You got cowboys up from Mexico.

74
00:05:18.276 --> 00:05:22.196
You got Indians and mixed bloods
and pretty rich boys from the East…

75
00:05:22.280 --> 00:05:23.323
[grunts]

76
00:05:23.406 --> 00:05:25.199
…murderers. and families.

77
00:05:25.700 --> 00:05:27.827
men of God. yeah. and widows.

78
00:05:28.328 --> 00:05:32.332
You got soldiers all ground up by the war.

79
00:05:33.541 --> 00:05:34.667
[Mr. Edwards exhales]

80
00:05:36.544 --> 00:05:37.420
There you go.

81
00:05:40.423 --> 00:05:42.425
Maybe it doesn't need
to belong to any of us.

82
00:05:43.551 --> 00:05:46.220
Maybe we just live our lives in peace.

83
00:05:48.056 --> 00:05:51.684
- Where's the security in that?
- Hm. Who said there's such a thing?

84
00:05:51.768 --> 00:05:52.769
Hm?

85
00:05:59.192 --> 00:06:00.026
You fought?

86
00:06:01.235 --> 00:06:02.153
In war?

87
00:06:02.737 --> 00:06:04.739
[melancholy music playing]

88
00:06:06.115 --> 00:06:07.241
My brothers did.

89
00:06:12.038 --> 00:06:14.248
Youngest was 13. George.

90
00:06:15.375 --> 00:06:17.001
Ran away to be a drummer boy.

91
00:06:21.506 --> 00:06:25.009
Well. you were smart
to stay out of the whole mess.

92
00:06:26.761 --> 00:06:28.221
Wish I'd done the same.

93
00:06:34.727 --> 00:06:37.772
[Mary inhales excitedly] Or we can
name her Jane. after Jane Eyre.

94
00:06:37.855 --> 00:06:40.942
Or what about Dolly. like Dolly Varden?
And if her eyes are blue.

95
00:06:41.025 --> 00:06:44.529
you can give her your pink ribbons.
And if they're brown. I can give her mine.

96
00:06:44.612 --> 00:06:47.782
I'm not giving my ribbons
to some baby we don't want.

97
00:06:48.574 --> 00:06:49.867
I want her.

98
00:06:49.951 --> 00:06:53.746
I want a real sister.
one who lets me teach her to read and sew

99
00:06:53.830 --> 00:06:55.415
and one who lets me braid her hair

100
00:06:55.498 --> 00:06:57.959
and cuddles. doesn't tease me
or get me into trouble

101
00:06:58.042 --> 00:07:00.920
or hog up all
of Pa's attention all the time.

102
00:07:05.133 --> 00:07:06.717
Pa doesn't want a girl.

103
00:07:07.760 --> 00:07:08.970
He wants a boy.

104
00:07:09.470 --> 00:07:11.889
I guess then
you wouldn't be the favorite anymore.

105
00:07:11.973 --> 00:07:14.475
[emotional music playing]

106
00:07:19.856 --> 00:07:21.858
[both grunting]

107
00:07:49.719 --> 00:07:51.512
Thought your stomach might be rumblin'.

108
00:07:56.601 --> 00:07:58.603
[music fades]

109
00:07:59.687 --> 00:08:02.356
Your pa says you're to thank
for this tasty rabbit…

110
00:08:02.440 --> 00:08:03.357
[grunts]

111
00:08:03.441 --> 00:08:05.151
…'cause you're a world-class hunter.

112
00:08:06.652 --> 00:08:09.489
He gave me a slingshot
for my birthday last year.

113
00:08:10.072 --> 00:08:13.784
Maybe you can give me some tips.
help me save some bullets.

114
00:08:15.620 --> 00:08:18.831
Pa really wants a boy. so…

115
00:08:21.626 --> 00:08:24.504
if I have a brother.
I'll probably have to give it away to him.

116
00:08:26.756 --> 00:08:28.424
[Mr. Edwards] Well. this is Kansas.

117
00:08:29.926 --> 00:08:33.179
Time he's old enough.
have you ready for your own rifle.

118
00:08:33.262 --> 00:08:34.722
maybe a bow and arrow.

119
00:08:40.811 --> 00:08:42.605
Have you shot a bow and arrow?

120
00:08:43.648 --> 00:08:45.566
Well. I've shot just about everything.

121
00:08:47.235 --> 00:08:50.863
You seem like the adventurous type.
Found the secret road yet?

122
00:08:51.572 --> 00:08:53.574
[heartwarming music playing]

123
00:09:01.666 --> 00:09:02.500
Wow.

124
00:09:03.543 --> 00:09:04.794
An Osage road.

125
00:09:05.836 --> 00:09:07.964
Prairie swallows it up in the summer.

126
00:09:10.049 --> 00:09:12.593
They use it to travel back home
after the hunt's done.

127
00:09:23.062 --> 00:09:25.356
- Where does it go?
- I don't know.

128
00:09:26.482 --> 00:09:28.401
Always wanted to follow it. though.

129
00:09:31.571 --> 00:09:33.531
- Maybe it leads to another world.
- Hm.

130
00:09:35.449 --> 00:09:37.368
I ever disappear. this is where I'll be.

131
00:09:39.745 --> 00:09:41.455
Lookin' for the end of this road.

132
00:09:43.165 --> 00:09:44.875
Lookin' for that other world.

133
00:09:52.216 --> 00:09:54.343
[music fades]

134
00:09:54.427 --> 00:09:55.428
[Mr. Edwards] Mm.

135
00:09:55.928 --> 00:09:56.762
Thank you.

136
00:09:58.472 --> 00:09:59.390
Hm.

137
00:10:00.057 --> 00:10:02.602
I always thought my wife made
the world's best cornbread.

138
00:10:02.685 --> 00:10:04.729
but I have to reconsider. Mary.

139
00:10:04.812 --> 00:10:05.938
Thank you.

140
00:10:10.526 --> 00:10:12.528
[tense music playing]

141
00:10:15.364 --> 00:10:16.365
[Charles] To new friends.

142
00:10:17.658 --> 00:10:18.492
Thank you.

143
00:10:19.201 --> 00:10:20.119
[music fades]

144
00:10:23.331 --> 00:10:26.083
Well. uh. someone told me
you play the fiddle.

145
00:10:27.043 --> 00:10:29.128
["Weevily Wheat" playing]

146
00:10:31.172 --> 00:10:32.048
[Laura laughs]

147
00:10:35.801 --> 00:10:39.305
<i>♪ I don't want your weevily wheat</i>
<i>I don't want your barley ♪</i>

148
00:10:39.388 --> 00:10:43.309
<i>♪ I'll take some flour in half an hour</i>
<i>And bake a cake for Charlie ♪</i>

149
00:10:45.269 --> 00:10:48.773
<i>♪ Charlie. he's a nice young man</i>
<i>Charlie. he's a dandy ♪</i>

150
00:10:48.856 --> 00:10:52.151
<i>♪ Every time he goes to town</i>
<i>He brings the girls some candy ♪</i>

151
00:10:52.234 --> 00:10:56.072
<i>♪ I don't want your weevily wheat</i>
<i>I don't want your barley ♪</i>

152
00:10:56.155 --> 00:11:00.159
<i>♪ I'll take some flour in half an hour</i>
<i>And bake a cake for Charlie ♪</i>

153
00:11:00.242 --> 00:11:01.911
[Mary and Laura laughing]

154
00:11:02.703 --> 00:11:04.622
- [Charles] Hey!
- [exclaiming]

155
00:11:04.705 --> 00:11:06.999
[Mary and Laura laughing]

156
00:11:07.083 --> 00:11:08.542
[girls] See you tomorrow.

157
00:11:08.626 --> 00:11:10.628
[emotional music playing]

158
00:11:19.303 --> 00:11:21.305
- [Laura] Mr. Edwards!
- Hey.

159
00:11:21.389 --> 00:11:22.682
[Jack barks]

160
00:11:22.765 --> 00:11:25.685
- [Laura] Hey!
- Hey. Hey. Hey. Hi. Hi.

161
00:11:27.353 --> 00:11:28.229
Go on here.

162
00:11:30.648 --> 00:11:31.774
Yeah! [laughs]

163
00:11:31.857 --> 00:11:33.901
[jaunty music playing]

164
00:11:37.863 --> 00:11:38.864
[Mr. Edwards grunts]

165
00:11:40.866 --> 00:11:42.702
That's it. As tight as you can.

166
00:11:44.662 --> 00:11:46.831
[Charles grunting]

167
00:11:49.208 --> 00:11:51.335
[jaunty music continues]

168
00:12:00.845 --> 00:12:02.722
- [Mary laughs]
- [Mr. Edwards] No?

169
00:12:14.817 --> 00:12:16.736
- Mr. Edwards!
- [Mr. Edwards] Hey!

170
00:12:17.236 --> 00:12:18.404
Nice work.

171
00:12:18.487 --> 00:12:19.530
Thanks.

172
00:12:22.283 --> 00:12:23.284
[exhales sharply]

173
00:12:32.126 --> 00:12:34.587
[birds chirping]

174
00:12:36.589 --> 00:12:38.591
[horse whinnies]

175
00:12:40.259 --> 00:12:42.178
[music fades]

176
00:12:42.261 --> 00:12:44.054
Whoa. Whoa.

177
00:12:44.597 --> 00:12:45.598
- Thank you.
- Yeah.

178
00:12:45.681 --> 00:12:46.515
Yeah.

179
00:12:48.642 --> 00:12:49.477
Hey.

180
00:12:56.650 --> 00:12:58.903
- Are you friends with them?
- I am.

181
00:12:59.653 --> 00:13:00.821
[Laura] I know that girl.

182
00:13:00.905 --> 00:13:03.449
I don't know her name.
but I found her doll.

183
00:13:04.575 --> 00:13:07.953
Ma says I can't go meet her.
because she doesn't want any trouble.

184
00:13:08.454 --> 00:13:12.541
Well. her name is Good Eagle.
And I think you'd like each other.

185
00:13:16.587 --> 00:13:18.422
And I had a litter of kittens born.

186
00:13:19.131 --> 00:13:22.718
Still too little to leave their ma yet.
but maybe you wanna come visit.

187
00:13:22.802 --> 00:13:23.719
pick one out.

188
00:13:24.762 --> 00:13:26.263
Good Eagle's gonna take one.

189
00:13:27.181 --> 00:13:28.891
Maybe you could choose together.

190
00:13:30.810 --> 00:13:33.771
I'll ask your pa. all right?
Just leave it with me.

191
00:13:44.740 --> 00:13:47.076
[horse whinnies]

192
00:13:51.497 --> 00:13:53.958
Caroline Ingalls. [sighs]

193
00:13:54.542 --> 00:13:55.960
Jemma James.

194
00:13:56.043 --> 00:13:58.838
A little bird told me
you've been having a rough time of it.

195
00:13:58.921 --> 00:14:02.341
so I thought
I should introduce myself properly.

196
00:14:03.175 --> 00:14:04.176
[sighs]

197
00:14:05.553 --> 00:14:07.012
[exhales]

198
00:14:07.096 --> 00:14:10.516
I come bearing gifts.

199
00:14:11.892 --> 00:14:14.728
Well. thank you. That… that's so kind. Um…

200
00:14:15.938 --> 00:14:18.691
- Would you like some coffee?
- Oh! Yes.

201
00:14:19.692 --> 00:14:22.862
Of course. I hated to leave St. Louis.
but my husband's a railroad man.

202
00:14:22.945 --> 00:14:25.197
- And where he goes. I follow.
- I know the feeling.

203
00:14:25.281 --> 00:14:29.493
It can get so lonely out here.
No community. no simple comforts.

204
00:14:30.703 --> 00:14:32.872
The men don't seem to mind. do they?

205
00:14:33.372 --> 00:14:34.206
No.

206
00:14:34.957 --> 00:14:38.294
Which is why it's up to
the women to make it happen.

207
00:14:38.377 --> 00:14:40.796
Our Women's Society
has big plans for Independence.

208
00:14:40.880 --> 00:14:46.510
A church. a school. a lending library.
and a temperance association.

209
00:14:46.594 --> 00:14:48.679
We're even trying to get the vote.

210
00:14:48.762 --> 00:14:51.223
You were a teacher.
weren't you. back in Wisconsin?

211
00:14:51.307 --> 00:14:54.018
- Yeah. Before I had children. yes.
- Do you ever miss it?

212
00:14:54.101 --> 00:14:55.519
I miss a lot of things.

213
00:14:55.603 --> 00:14:58.647
My sisters. my mother. my house.

214
00:14:59.148 --> 00:15:01.734
a place to belong. a working foot.

215
00:15:02.234 --> 00:15:03.611
You're not alone.

216
00:15:03.694 --> 00:15:06.113
We all miss our old lives.

217
00:15:06.196 --> 00:15:09.074
But we can build new ones. can't we?
Better ones.

218
00:15:10.284 --> 00:15:11.577
- I hope so.
- Hm.

219
00:15:13.454 --> 00:15:14.705
Oh. don't you dare.

220
00:15:17.374 --> 00:15:18.375
[sighs]

221
00:15:23.964 --> 00:15:26.717
I see you have
John Edwards working for you.

222
00:15:26.800 --> 00:15:28.844
Mm. Yes.
He and Charles are making a trade.

223
00:15:28.928 --> 00:15:32.056
Once they finish with this house.
they're gonna start working on his.

224
00:15:32.139 --> 00:15:35.726
He's been a godsend. My girls are smitten.

225
00:15:35.809 --> 00:15:37.144
Hm. Yes.

226
00:15:38.395 --> 00:15:40.648
I'd be careful if I were you.

227
00:15:40.731 --> 00:15:43.817
I'm sure I don't wanna spread
any ugly ideas about people.

228
00:15:43.901 --> 00:15:47.529
but he's not the kind of man
you want near your family.

229
00:15:50.449 --> 00:15:54.244
He makes whiskey.
Nips quite a bit of it himself.

230
00:15:54.328 --> 00:15:56.747
I can't tell you how many times
someone has found him

231
00:15:56.830 --> 00:15:58.749
full as a tick on Main Street.

232
00:16:01.794 --> 00:16:03.587
Just because we landed
in the middle of nowhere

233
00:16:03.671 --> 00:16:06.340
doesn't mean we should give up
the ideals we value.

234
00:16:06.423 --> 00:16:10.010
Wouldn't you agree? But maybe I'm wrong.
Maybe he's a changed man.

235
00:16:10.094 --> 00:16:13.847
Who am I to tell tales?
Will you let me come again. Caroline?

236
00:16:13.931 --> 00:16:15.307
- Of course. yes.
- [Jemma chuckles]

237
00:16:15.391 --> 00:16:16.308
Oh.

238
00:16:16.392 --> 00:16:20.354
And don't worry. I know a young man
from a very respectable family in Boston

239
00:16:20.437 --> 00:16:22.314
who can help your husband with the house.

240
00:16:22.398 --> 00:16:24.108
You just say the word.

241
00:16:26.110 --> 00:16:27.194
Oh.

242
00:16:27.277 --> 00:16:28.988
- Thank you.
- [Jemma] Yes. of course.

243
00:16:30.572 --> 00:16:35.411
[Mr. Edwards and Charles grunting]

244
00:16:37.955 --> 00:16:39.248
[grunting]

245
00:16:39.331 --> 00:16:40.416
[Charles cries out]

246
00:16:40.499 --> 00:16:41.917
[tense music playing]

247
00:16:45.462 --> 00:16:46.964
- You all right?
- Sorry. sorry.

248
00:16:47.047 --> 00:16:48.465
That was… That was careless.

249
00:16:48.549 --> 00:16:52.136
- You need a break?
- No. No. Let's keep goin'.

250
00:16:52.845 --> 00:16:53.679
Yeah.

251
00:16:55.973 --> 00:16:57.099
[grunting]

252
00:16:58.642 --> 00:17:01.061
[both grunting. panting]

253
00:17:04.690 --> 00:17:06.692
[music fades]

254
00:17:07.359 --> 00:17:08.485
[Mr. Edwards exhales deeply]

255
00:17:08.569 --> 00:17:09.820
Mr. Edwards?

256
00:17:09.903 --> 00:17:11.739
- Yeah?
- [Jack barking]

257
00:17:13.699 --> 00:17:17.411
Do you happen to know anything
about the boy at the General Store?

258
00:17:17.494 --> 00:17:18.579
Caleb?

259
00:17:20.581 --> 00:17:24.710
Turned up all skinny and scabby
a few months ago. so Emily took him in.

260
00:17:25.586 --> 00:17:28.714
Doesn't say much.
Plays a fierce game of chess.

261
00:17:29.214 --> 00:17:33.052
I will admit to being a pretty poor chess
player though. so maybe he's only fair.

262
00:17:33.135 --> 00:17:34.678
[Mary laughs]

263
00:17:37.139 --> 00:17:38.432
Could you give this to him?

264
00:17:46.482 --> 00:17:47.858
You leave this with me.

265
00:18:07.127 --> 00:18:09.379
- [Charles] You had a visitor today.
- Mm-hm.

266
00:18:09.463 --> 00:18:10.923
Jemma James.

267
00:18:11.965 --> 00:18:14.176
She runs the Women's Society in town.

268
00:18:14.968 --> 00:18:18.806
They're building a church.
a school. a lending library.

269
00:18:19.306 --> 00:18:22.559
- She asked if I might like to join.
- They'd be lucky to have you.

270
00:18:23.811 --> 00:18:25.354
And she has two girls at home.

271
00:18:25.854 --> 00:18:27.940
She says she'll invite
Laura and Mary to visit.

272
00:18:30.651 --> 00:18:32.861
Nice to have people around
that feel like family. isn't it?

273
00:18:47.167 --> 00:18:48.919
[cheerful fiddle music playing]

274
00:18:53.382 --> 00:18:55.384
[Mary and Laura laughing]

275
00:19:15.904 --> 00:19:17.906
[melancholy music plays over fiddle music]

276
00:19:29.585 --> 00:19:30.586
[fiddle music ends]

277
00:19:30.669 --> 00:19:32.963
- [Caroline laughs]
- [everyone clapping]

278
00:19:36.133 --> 00:19:38.260
Ooh! Think I need my coat.

279
00:19:39.178 --> 00:19:40.262
Back in a flash.

280
00:19:55.694 --> 00:19:57.237
[breathes deeply]

281
00:20:00.407 --> 00:20:01.867
[footsteps approaching]

282
00:20:04.077 --> 00:20:04.953
Hm.

283
00:20:06.205 --> 00:20:07.164
Mm.

284
00:20:08.207 --> 00:20:09.625
[clears throat. smacks lips]

285
00:20:10.542 --> 00:20:13.503
I'd never take a drop during the day.
but in the evenings…

286
00:20:13.587 --> 00:20:14.713
[sniffs]

287
00:20:14.796 --> 00:20:17.007
…just need somethin'
to chase the shakes away.

288
00:20:17.507 --> 00:20:19.509
[breathing heavily]

289
00:20:21.303 --> 00:20:23.305
[melancholy music continues]

290
00:20:30.354 --> 00:20:34.733
When I was a girl. my father sailed goods
for a living on Lake Michigan.

291
00:20:35.859 --> 00:20:38.779
His captain always needed something
to chase the shakes away.

292
00:20:43.242 --> 00:20:47.496
One night he set them off in a storm
any sober fool could've seen coming.

293
00:20:48.789 --> 00:20:50.040
The boat broke up.

294
00:20:51.041 --> 00:20:52.125
They all drowned.

295
00:20:59.758 --> 00:21:00.676
I'm sorry.

296
00:21:03.553 --> 00:21:06.682
You can't imagine the kind
of life we tumbled into.

297
00:21:08.058 --> 00:21:09.101
Alone.

298
00:21:10.102 --> 00:21:13.021
Starving. Cold to the bone.

299
00:21:14.856 --> 00:21:16.650
Everyone was very sorry.

300
00:21:20.404 --> 00:21:26.159
I swear on my life. I would never ever
do anything to put your family in danger.

301
00:21:30.080 --> 00:21:31.873
That's what the captain told my mother.

302
00:21:32.791 --> 00:21:33.792
[music fades]

303
00:21:34.710 --> 00:21:36.712
[fiddle music playing]

304
00:22:03.363 --> 00:22:05.407
Well. time to get goin' home.

305
00:22:05.490 --> 00:22:07.534
- Stay for one more song?
- [Mr. Edwards grunts]

306
00:22:08.118 --> 00:22:11.121
Oh. I gotta check on those kittens.

307
00:22:14.416 --> 00:22:16.752
- Walk with me a ways.
- Sure.

308
00:22:19.254 --> 00:22:21.173
See you tomorrow! Good night!

309
00:22:21.256 --> 00:22:22.174
Good night!

310
00:22:25.385 --> 00:22:28.180
Everything all right?
Am I working you too hard?

311
00:22:28.263 --> 00:22:30.140
[Mr. Edwards] No. nothing like that.

312
00:22:31.224 --> 00:22:33.310
You know. besides you and Mitchell.

313
00:22:33.393 --> 00:22:37.522
I don't think anyone around here really
cares if I wake up in the mornin' or not.

314
00:22:39.775 --> 00:22:41.610
I don't come by friends easily.

315
00:22:41.693 --> 00:22:43.362
[emotional music playing]

316
00:22:43.445 --> 00:22:45.947
I don't let myself come by friends easily.

317
00:23:04.549 --> 00:23:06.551
[wolf howls]

318
00:23:07.761 --> 00:23:10.222
[birds chirping]

319
00:23:24.403 --> 00:23:26.154
Why didn't he come. Pa?

320
00:23:30.492 --> 00:23:32.577
He probably just needed a day to himself.

321
00:23:38.875 --> 00:23:40.877
[emotional music continues]

322
00:24:06.486 --> 00:24:07.779
Maybe we should go see.

323
00:24:16.955 --> 00:24:18.248
[music fades]

324
00:24:18.331 --> 00:24:19.332
[horse neighing]

325
00:24:22.043 --> 00:24:23.003
Thank you.

326
00:24:24.754 --> 00:24:26.715
[kittens meowing]

327
00:24:32.471 --> 00:24:34.014
They're so cute.

328
00:24:34.764 --> 00:24:36.808
That one looks like a potato.

329
00:24:36.892 --> 00:24:38.477
[both giggling]

330
00:24:39.686 --> 00:24:41.521
- I'm Laura.
- Good Eagle.

331
00:24:42.731 --> 00:24:44.024
I like your hat.

332
00:24:45.108 --> 00:24:48.028
It was my cousin Jean's.
but his head got too big.

333
00:24:48.111 --> 00:24:50.906
so he gave it to me last Christmas.

334
00:24:52.240 --> 00:24:53.867
I miss him less when I wear it.

335
00:24:56.119 --> 00:24:58.622
[Good Eagle] Are you gonna take a kitten
when they're old enough?

336
00:24:58.705 --> 00:24:59.539
[Laura] Maybe.

337
00:25:00.832 --> 00:25:05.128
- I don't know if my dog would like it.
- You're lucky. I wish we had a dog.

338
00:25:05.212 --> 00:25:06.755
His name is Jack.

339
00:25:08.048 --> 00:25:10.008
You could come visit him sometime.

340
00:25:12.511 --> 00:25:14.638
Edwards hasn't shown for a few days.

341
00:25:14.721 --> 00:25:17.641
He tends to go off
selling his whiskey once a month.

342
00:25:17.724 --> 00:25:19.392
sometimes as far as Oswego.

343
00:25:20.018 --> 00:25:21.520
Or he could be wolfing.

344
00:25:22.687 --> 00:25:23.563
Nah. I wouldn't worry.

345
00:25:24.898 --> 00:25:27.234
He tends to… turn up.

346
00:25:28.985 --> 00:25:31.613
I would worry about the kittens.

347
00:25:31.696 --> 00:25:32.614
[laughs]

348
00:25:32.697 --> 00:25:35.492
[William] Mine hasn't stopped
talking about them for the past week.

349
00:25:35.575 --> 00:25:38.954
I don't know what will happen
if I don't let her take at least two.

350
00:25:39.037 --> 00:25:41.456
[both chuckle]

351
00:25:55.136 --> 00:25:58.598
Back home. we wouldn't think twice
about someone shining off for a few days.

352
00:26:00.559 --> 00:26:03.520
Edwards is just used to
being on his own schedule.

353
00:26:05.063 --> 00:26:06.481
I'm sure he'll turn up soon.

354
00:26:08.567 --> 00:26:09.901
He's not coming back.

355
00:26:11.111 --> 00:26:11.945
What?

356
00:26:14.531 --> 00:26:19.077
He was drinking. here at our home.
He said he didn't do it while you worked.

357
00:26:19.160 --> 00:26:21.288
- But I… I didn't believe him. so--
- What'd you say?

358
00:26:23.957 --> 00:26:24.833
[exhales shakily]

359
00:26:24.916 --> 00:26:26.084
I told him not to come back

360
00:26:26.167 --> 00:26:28.295
until he didn't need something
to chase the shakes away.

361
00:26:28.378 --> 00:26:31.298
It doesn't work like that. You don't snap
your fingers and make it go away.

362
00:26:34.384 --> 00:26:35.677
His wife is gone.

363
00:26:36.303 --> 00:26:39.848
His girls are gone. He got chewed up
and spit out by the godforsaken war.

364
00:26:39.931 --> 00:26:40.890
- You knew?
- And…

365
00:26:42.309 --> 00:26:45.729
- You knew and you didn't say anything?
- Caroline. we are alone at sea.

366
00:26:46.771 --> 00:26:48.481
We don't have room
for obsession with virtue.

367
00:26:48.565 --> 00:26:49.816
It's not virtue!

368
00:26:49.899 --> 00:26:53.361
- I don't wanna lose my family again.
- We can't finish this house without him.

369
00:26:54.654 --> 00:26:57.282
You have to open your mind.
or we are all gonna drown here.

370
00:26:57.365 --> 00:27:00.076
What you do is dangerous.

371
00:27:01.161 --> 00:27:04.956
It's dangerous! Look what can happen
even when you're stone-cold sober!

372
00:27:05.457 --> 00:27:09.919
I will not see you dead because you want
to save another broken person.

373
00:27:11.546 --> 00:27:14.924
He isn't George.
You can't bring your brother back.

374
00:27:15.008 --> 00:27:17.010
[melancholy music playing]

375
00:27:26.978 --> 00:27:29.356
- Let me come with you.
- No.

376
00:27:29.939 --> 00:27:30.857
Please.

377
00:27:33.568 --> 00:27:34.861
Stay here and look after your ma.

378
00:27:35.612 --> 00:27:36.696
[horse snorts]

379
00:28:01.096 --> 00:28:02.097
Hello.

380
00:28:03.932 --> 00:28:05.058
[music fades]

381
00:28:05.141 --> 00:28:09.104
Charles Ingalls. Sorry to intrude.
I'm looking for your husband.

382
00:28:09.771 --> 00:28:11.022
Is Laura with you?

383
00:28:13.233 --> 00:28:16.695
- [in Osage] Don't talk to strangers.
- He's not a stranger.

384
00:28:17.570 --> 00:28:19.531
He's Mr. Ingalls.

385
00:28:21.866 --> 00:28:22.951
[in English] He's not here.

386
00:28:43.680 --> 00:28:45.682
[pensive music playing]

387
00:28:46.516 --> 00:28:47.559
I need your help.

388
00:28:55.066 --> 00:28:56.317
I could help look.

389
00:29:00.363 --> 00:29:03.199
I saved some of the cake
and jam Mrs. James brought.

390
00:29:08.663 --> 00:29:11.791
You and Mary run down to the creek
for water. We'll have the rest of it.

391
00:29:12.417 --> 00:29:13.251
All right?

392
00:29:25.847 --> 00:29:28.725
Pa will find him.
Pa always knows where to look.

393
00:29:29.476 --> 00:29:30.894
Remember Uncle George?

394
00:29:31.394 --> 00:29:34.439
He was always running off.
and Pa always brought him home.

395
00:29:35.565 --> 00:29:38.234
Mr. Edwards wouldn't just
disappear like that.

396
00:29:41.613 --> 00:29:43.615
[inquisitive music playing]

397
00:29:44.991 --> 00:29:45.825
What?

398
00:29:51.164 --> 00:29:52.290
What is this?

399
00:29:53.333 --> 00:29:54.876
A secret Osage road.

400
00:29:56.336 --> 00:29:59.672
Mr. Edwards said if he ever disappeared.
this is where he'd be.

401
00:30:03.134 --> 00:30:04.385
I don't know.

402
00:30:10.266 --> 00:30:12.685
Okay. We should follow it. then.

403
00:30:18.900 --> 00:30:19.734
Come on.

404
00:30:22.654 --> 00:30:23.488
[music fades]

405
00:30:23.571 --> 00:30:26.616
I didn't know who else to ask.
I know he considers you a friend.

406
00:30:26.699 --> 00:30:28.868
I have an idea where he might be.

407
00:30:30.453 --> 00:30:32.789
I don't think I made
a very good impression on your wife.

408
00:30:32.872 --> 00:30:36.000
Don't take it personally.
She doesn't much like any of the outsiders

409
00:30:36.084 --> 00:30:38.753
chewing up her land
like a swarm of locusts.

410
00:30:39.254 --> 00:30:40.213
Her words.

411
00:30:40.296 --> 00:30:41.548
You're Osage.

412
00:30:41.631 --> 00:30:44.259
- [William] That's right.
- You don't feel the same way?

413
00:30:44.342 --> 00:30:46.135
I don't see any sense in making enemies

414
00:30:46.219 --> 00:30:48.888
of the people who are gonna take
what they want anyway.

415
00:30:48.972 --> 00:30:51.641
I don't wanna be shuffled around
from one place to another.

416
00:30:51.724 --> 00:30:54.352
I'd rather try and be a part
of the future of this country.

417
00:30:54.435 --> 00:30:56.604
[Charles] Your house is the nicest
I've seen.

418
00:30:57.272 --> 00:31:00.191
[William] My father helped me build it.
right after the war.

419
00:31:00.275 --> 00:31:01.776
Put everything he had into it.

420
00:31:02.819 --> 00:31:05.321
Couldn't bear to stay around
after my mother died.

421
00:31:06.573 --> 00:31:09.951
My wife's not sold on it yet.
The future. not the house.

422
00:31:11.828 --> 00:31:13.955
- I know the feeling.
- [chuckles]

423
00:31:15.123 --> 00:31:16.207
Whoa.

424
00:31:19.210 --> 00:31:20.712
[Charles] Is that where we're going?

425
00:31:20.795 --> 00:31:24.465
His most reliable buyer.
among other things.

426
00:31:25.758 --> 00:31:26.634
Mmm.

427
00:31:42.734 --> 00:31:44.444
How far does it go?

428
00:31:45.403 --> 00:31:46.487
I don't know.

429
00:31:47.196 --> 00:31:48.781
Maybe we should go back?

430
00:31:48.865 --> 00:31:51.576
["Weevily Wheat" playing on harmonica
in the distance]

431
00:31:55.079 --> 00:31:56.789
- Mr. Edwards!
- [Mary laughs]

432
00:31:56.873 --> 00:31:58.875
[hopeful music playing]

433
00:32:02.462 --> 00:32:03.296
This way!

434
00:32:04.923 --> 00:32:05.757
Hurry!

435
00:32:09.135 --> 00:32:10.136
Come on.

436
00:32:30.573 --> 00:32:32.116
[Mary] There's no one here.

437
00:32:32.700 --> 00:32:34.118
We have to go back.

438
00:32:35.828 --> 00:32:38.081
Laura. we have to go back.

439
00:32:51.594 --> 00:32:52.971
[music fades]

440
00:32:53.054 --> 00:32:55.014
- [piano playing]
- [door opens]

441
00:32:55.098 --> 00:32:57.100
[indistinct chatter]

442
00:32:57.976 --> 00:32:59.310
[door closes]

443
00:32:59.394 --> 00:33:00.520
Ingalls. isn't it?

444
00:33:02.105 --> 00:33:04.524
Never figured you'd last a week out here.

445
00:33:08.069 --> 00:33:08.987
William.

446
00:33:09.821 --> 00:33:10.780
[in French] Who's this?

447
00:33:11.739 --> 00:33:14.450
[in English] Charles Ingalls.
this is Lacey Aubert.

448
00:33:14.534 --> 00:33:17.620
She and Edwards know each other.

449
00:33:19.580 --> 00:33:21.249
[in French] Something like that.

450
00:33:21.332 --> 00:33:22.458
[in English] Come on back.

451
00:33:26.504 --> 00:33:27.755
[William] Watch your head.

452
00:33:29.090 --> 00:33:30.049
[Lacey] He's gone.

453
00:33:31.092 --> 00:33:33.302
He pulled up stakes and headed north.

454
00:33:33.386 --> 00:33:34.929
He wouldn't say where.

455
00:33:35.513 --> 00:33:37.557
He sold me everything he had.

456
00:33:38.057 --> 00:33:39.684
And he finally bought a horse.

457
00:33:41.936 --> 00:33:44.647
The only thing
he left behind was a box of kittens.

458
00:33:44.731 --> 00:33:46.190
[sighs]

459
00:33:48.317 --> 00:33:51.029
I really thought he'd settled in
with you and your family.

460
00:33:52.864 --> 00:33:53.865
He mentioned us?

461
00:33:54.365 --> 00:33:57.618
[Lacey] He couldn't stop
talking about you and your girls.

462
00:33:58.119 --> 00:34:00.997
You made him feel like he had
a future to look forward to.

463
00:34:01.998 --> 00:34:03.708
like he mattered to someone.

464
00:34:05.918 --> 00:34:07.336
He's a good man.

465
00:34:08.838 --> 00:34:10.548
despite all appearances.

466
00:34:11.049 --> 00:34:13.468
- Wouldn't you say. William?
- I would.

467
00:34:16.596 --> 00:34:17.764
[in French] A good friend.

468
00:34:20.475 --> 00:34:22.435
[in English] It's good to know
he's all right.

469
00:34:23.019 --> 00:34:25.271
That's the thing out here. Mr. Ingalls.

470
00:34:26.689 --> 00:34:28.066
People come and go.

471
00:34:28.900 --> 00:34:30.818
And you have to make your peace with that.

472
00:34:30.902 --> 00:34:32.904
[melancholy music playing]

473
00:34:42.455 --> 00:34:43.539
Where's the trail?

474
00:34:51.130 --> 00:34:52.006
This way.

475
00:34:53.883 --> 00:34:55.259
We came from this way.

476
00:34:56.385 --> 00:34:57.553
[Mary] Are you sure?

477
00:35:04.268 --> 00:35:05.353
[Caroline] Mary!

478
00:35:05.436 --> 00:35:06.437
Laura!

479
00:35:06.521 --> 00:35:08.856
[breathing heavily]

480
00:35:09.649 --> 00:35:10.650
Oh…

481
00:35:18.866 --> 00:35:21.661
I thought I'd bring
the lending library to you.

482
00:35:21.744 --> 00:35:24.747
Or a selection anyway.
We even have newspapers.

483
00:35:27.166 --> 00:35:28.334
What is it? What's wrong?

484
00:35:29.877 --> 00:35:32.380
The girls went to get water.
and they haven't come back.

485
00:35:32.463 --> 00:35:33.548
[Caroline sobs]

486
00:35:34.507 --> 00:35:37.802
I'll run down to the creek and fetch them.
Everything's going to be just fine.

487
00:35:40.054 --> 00:35:42.056
- [cues horse]
- [horse neighs]

488
00:36:04.370 --> 00:36:07.165
You have no idea where we are. do you?

489
00:36:16.007 --> 00:36:19.802
Guess a real sister
wouldn't have gotten you lost and hungry.

490
00:36:32.732 --> 00:36:37.987
Maybe that sister wouldn't have been
brave enough to look in the first place.

491
00:36:57.006 --> 00:36:59.717
Just need to find a road
before it gets dark.

492
00:37:08.601 --> 00:37:12.772
The last thing in the world I wanted to do
was send a troubled man into more trouble.

493
00:37:14.523 --> 00:37:15.858
I made that mistake once.

494
00:37:15.942 --> 00:37:18.861
Hey. he'd been running a long time
before he landed here.

495
00:37:19.862 --> 00:37:22.156
I'm not sure he ever intended to stay.

496
00:37:22.240 --> 00:37:23.366
[music fades]

497
00:37:23.449 --> 00:37:25.785
[buggy approaching]

498
00:37:27.536 --> 00:37:29.914
Charles Ingalls. your girls are missing.

499
00:37:29.997 --> 00:37:33.376
They went for water and didn't come back.
I'm rounding up a search party.

500
00:37:34.377 --> 00:37:36.212
Send them to the creek.
We'll spread from there.

501
00:37:36.796 --> 00:37:38.256
[tense music playing]

502
00:37:47.765 --> 00:37:50.768
[Caroline sobbing] I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

503
00:37:52.603 --> 00:37:53.813
[Charles] We'll find them.

504
00:37:56.023 --> 00:37:56.983
We'll find them.

505
00:37:57.066 --> 00:37:59.068
[Caroline sobs]

506
00:38:02.738 --> 00:38:05.283
- [man 1] Mary!
- [Charles] Laura!

507
00:38:05.366 --> 00:38:07.994
The others have moved
all the way down the bend.

508
00:38:08.494 --> 00:38:10.079
- Girls!
- Mary!

509
00:38:10.162 --> 00:38:11.289
- [man 2] Laura!
- [Jemma] Mary!

510
00:38:11.372 --> 00:38:12.748
- [man 3] Laura!
- [man 4] Laura!

511
00:38:13.791 --> 00:38:16.711
- [woman] Mary!
- Down there. you see? They went that way.

512
00:38:17.628 --> 00:38:18.754
Mary!

513
00:38:21.841 --> 00:38:22.842
Laura!

514
00:38:24.302 --> 00:38:26.429
- [man 1] Laura!
- [man 2] Laura!

515
00:38:26.512 --> 00:38:27.680
[man 3] Mary!

516
00:38:28.681 --> 00:38:29.807
Laura!

517
00:38:31.100 --> 00:38:32.059
Mary?

518
00:38:33.019 --> 00:38:33.978
Laura!

519
00:38:35.146 --> 00:38:36.439
- Laura!
- Mary!

520
00:38:36.522 --> 00:38:39.483
[people calling over each other]

521
00:38:41.694 --> 00:38:42.737
Laura!

522
00:38:44.488 --> 00:38:45.364
Mary!

523
00:38:51.370 --> 00:38:52.246
[bird chirping]

524
00:38:54.832 --> 00:38:55.875
[music fades]

525
00:38:55.958 --> 00:38:57.960
[harmonica music playing]

526
00:39:06.469 --> 00:39:08.471
[woman exclaims]

527
00:39:16.937 --> 00:39:18.731
Now. who's that watching?

528
00:39:21.442 --> 00:39:22.651
Come closer.

529
00:39:23.861 --> 00:39:24.695
Come on.

530
00:39:27.073 --> 00:39:27.907
Come on.

531
00:39:37.249 --> 00:39:39.335
We're looking for Mr. Edwards.

532
00:39:39.418 --> 00:39:40.961
[tense music playing]

533
00:39:45.424 --> 00:39:47.760
Oh. sure! Edwards is with us.

534
00:39:47.843 --> 00:39:49.637
- He is?
- Oh yeah.

535
00:39:49.720 --> 00:39:51.514
He's gone off hunting.

536
00:39:51.597 --> 00:39:54.600
but he'll be back soon
now that it's getting dark.

537
00:39:54.683 --> 00:39:57.311
Why don't you come sit
by the fire and wait?

538
00:40:01.482 --> 00:40:02.691
Are you hungry?

539
00:40:03.192 --> 00:40:04.026
Eat up.

540
00:40:05.194 --> 00:40:06.362
It's good.

541
00:40:06.445 --> 00:40:08.364
[ominous music playing]

542
00:40:11.951 --> 00:40:13.994
What's your name. sweetheart?

543
00:40:18.958 --> 00:40:19.875
Mary.

544
00:40:19.959 --> 00:40:21.168
Mary.

545
00:40:21.752 --> 00:40:24.672
Well. come on. Mary. Come sit by me.

546
00:40:39.687 --> 00:40:42.064
- We should get back to our pa.
- Your pa?

547
00:40:42.982 --> 00:40:44.400
- No!
- [Mary gasps]

548
00:40:44.483 --> 00:40:46.068
Not safe out there with the wolves!

549
00:40:46.152 --> 00:40:48.320
[grunts. gasps]

550
00:40:50.239 --> 00:40:52.450
- [Laura] Let go of me!
- [woman screams]

551
00:40:52.533 --> 00:40:54.577
- Ungrateful little tick!
- [Mr. Edwards] Hey!

552
00:40:55.703 --> 00:40:56.787
Back off!

553
00:41:02.585 --> 00:41:03.752
No trouble.

554
00:41:03.836 --> 00:41:05.171
No trouble here.

555
00:41:07.089 --> 00:41:08.424
[melancholy music playing]

556
00:41:09.675 --> 00:41:11.635
It's okay. Mary. Okay.

557
00:41:12.928 --> 00:41:13.762
Go on.

558
00:41:20.519 --> 00:41:22.021
[laughs]

559
00:41:25.274 --> 00:41:27.193
[searchers calling in the distance]

560
00:41:27.276 --> 00:41:30.196
[animals howling]

561
00:41:35.659 --> 00:41:38.662
[footsteps approaching]

562
00:41:39.830 --> 00:41:41.415
[Caroline] Mary! Laura!

563
00:41:43.876 --> 00:41:45.002
Run on home.

564
00:41:50.174 --> 00:41:51.175
[Caroline] Oh.

565
00:41:53.010 --> 00:41:54.386
Go on. I'll watch.

566
00:41:54.970 --> 00:41:56.430
Where were you?

567
00:41:58.766 --> 00:42:00.059
Why did you leave?

568
00:42:03.145 --> 00:42:04.230
Your ma was right.

569
00:42:05.356 --> 00:42:06.565
I don't belong here.

570
00:42:07.733 --> 00:42:09.109
You do belong.

571
00:42:10.986 --> 00:42:12.655
I'm not your family.

572
00:42:14.406 --> 00:42:15.866
I'm not anyone's family.

573
00:42:18.827 --> 00:42:20.579
I thought we were friends.

574
00:42:27.795 --> 00:42:29.421
You don't need a friend like me.

575
00:42:32.591 --> 00:42:33.551
You're wrong.

576
00:42:36.804 --> 00:42:39.932
I know you think your pa would love
a boy more than you. but he won't.

577
00:42:47.856 --> 00:42:50.484
I wouldn't have traded my girls
for anything in the world.

578
00:42:53.237 --> 00:42:54.405
[Caroline] Mr. Edwards!

579
00:42:56.365 --> 00:42:57.616
Mr. Edwards!

580
00:43:02.246 --> 00:43:04.081
Please… please wait!

581
00:43:07.251 --> 00:43:08.085
Please.

582
00:43:08.961 --> 00:43:09.920
[horse neighing]

583
00:43:10.004 --> 00:43:11.255
I'm sorry.

584
00:43:12.214 --> 00:43:14.216
[horse galloping away]

585
00:43:18.262 --> 00:43:20.848
[Laura panting]

586
00:43:24.435 --> 00:43:26.437
[Laura cries]

587
00:43:27.438 --> 00:43:29.273
Are you all right? Are you all right?

588
00:43:29.356 --> 00:43:32.026
- Oh!
- [all sobbing]

589
00:43:32.735 --> 00:43:34.737
[tender music playing]

590
00:43:42.703 --> 00:43:43.829
[horse nickers]

591
00:43:43.912 --> 00:43:46.415
- I'll call off the search.
- Pa!

592
00:43:47.916 --> 00:43:49.627
- Are you hurt?
- [sobbing] No.

593
00:43:51.378 --> 00:43:53.756
Edwards said he didn't wanna be family.

594
00:43:54.548 --> 00:43:55.466
It's all right.

595
00:43:56.508 --> 00:43:58.093
Our family's perfect the way it is.

596
00:44:05.643 --> 00:44:06.602
We'll be fine.

597
00:44:07.645 --> 00:44:08.729
We'll all be fine.

598
00:44:11.607 --> 00:44:14.068
[birds chirping]

599
00:44:19.156 --> 00:44:20.407
You didn't sleep?

600
00:44:21.659 --> 00:44:22.826
Too much thinking.

601
00:44:23.494 --> 00:44:24.912
Did they find the girls?

602
00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:30.834
Hey…

603
00:44:33.045 --> 00:44:33.879
Good.

604
00:44:38.384 --> 00:44:40.386
[upbeat music playing]

605
00:44:42.054 --> 00:44:43.347
[horse whinnying]

606
00:44:45.391 --> 00:44:48.811
[Jemma] Mr. Ingalls. I've got just the man
to help you build your house.

607
00:44:48.894 --> 00:44:53.107
Meet Adam Scott. He was kind enough
to join the search party for your girls.

608
00:44:53.190 --> 00:44:54.066
[Charles] Thank you.

609
00:44:54.817 --> 00:44:57.152
I don't know much about much.
but I can learn.

610
00:44:58.821 --> 00:44:59.905
I look forward to it.

611
00:45:02.700 --> 00:45:03.701
Ugh.

612
00:45:03.784 --> 00:45:05.119
[Charles] Thank you. Mrs. James.

613
00:45:06.453 --> 00:45:08.706
- Would you like some coffee?
- [Adam] Yes. please.

614
00:45:08.789 --> 00:45:10.290
[Jack barking]

615
00:45:11.083 --> 00:45:14.420
<i>♪ I'll take some flour in half an hour ♪</i>

616
00:45:14.503 --> 00:45:17.214
<i>♪ And bake a cake for Charlie ♪</i>

617
00:45:17.297 --> 00:45:19.299
[upbeat music continues]

618
00:45:39.153 --> 00:45:40.779
[chuckles softly]

619
00:45:40.863 --> 00:45:42.239
[kittens meowing]

620
00:46:11.894 --> 00:46:13.896
The house is more than half built.

621
00:46:13.979 --> 00:46:14.938
We'll be safe.

622
00:46:15.022 --> 00:46:16.482
We'll be happy.

623
00:46:16.565 --> 00:46:17.858
[music ends]

624
00:46:22.613 --> 00:46:23.781
[hooves clopping]

625
00:46:23.864 --> 00:46:26.283
[unsettling music playing]

626
00:46:27.326 --> 00:46:29.953
[horses neighing]

627
00:46:38.045 --> 00:46:41.757
[dramatic swell]

628
00:46:44.051 --> 00:46:46.053
[pensive music playing]

629
00:47:12.538 --> 00:47:15.457
[stirring music playing]

630
00:47:36.478 --> 00:47:37.646
[music builds]

631
00:47:37.729 --> 00:47:38.647
[music fades]

632
00:47:38.730 --> 00:47:40.732
[closing theme music playing]

633
00:48:57.684 --> 00:48:58.727
[music ends]

634
00:48:59.305 --> 00:49:59.540
